               <p>WILLIAM JONES. I am a <rs id="t18260914-343-viclabel1931" type="occupation">couch and sofa bedstead-maker</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-343-victim1827 t18260914-343-viclabel1931"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18260914-343-crimeloc1932">Meed-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-343-crimeloc1932" type="placeName" value="Meed-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-343-crimeloc1932" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-343-off1929 t18260914-343-crimeloc1932"></join>. The prisoner was my <rs id="t18260914-343-deflabel1933" type="occupation">journeyman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-343-defend1826 t18260914-343-deflabel1933"></join>; these tools were on the bench; I missed the tools on the 24th of May; I had not seen the prisoner for a month before he was taken; I never suffered him to take them.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-343-person1828">
                  THOMAS 
                  BAYLIS
               <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1828" type="surname" value="BAYLIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1828" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1828" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am employed by Mr. Attenborough, a pawnbroker. I have some tools, pawned at our house, in the name of Smart, but I cannot swear to the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-343-person1829">
                  THOMAS 
                  WELLS
               <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1829" type="surname" value="WELLS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1829" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1829" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a japanner. I was going to Jones' house, to work, on the 24th of May, and saw the prisoner running along; I said, "Where are you going?" he said, to Shoreditch. I saw him drop a pair of pincers, which he picked up; I went to Mr. Jones', and found the things had been stolen; no other man worked there but myself.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-343-person1830">
                  SARAH 
                  JONES
               <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1830" type="surname" value="JONES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1830" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1830" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the wife of 
               <persName id="t18260914-343-person1831">
                  William 
                  Jones
               <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1831" type="surname" value="Jones"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1831" type="given" value="William"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-343-person1831" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was standing at the door on the 24th of May - the prisoner was working with the hammer and pincers - I told him to be careful of them, and the moment he was gone I missed them.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I never intended to steal them. - Mr. Jones and I had a few words in the morning, which induced me to leave; he went to Paddington, and said he would prosecute me to the utmost, and I was afraid to go back.</p>
